FUNCTIONS.DOC

This is documentation for all
GroundhoGrafix Power C Functions.

When you know the function name your
looking for I suggest to search using
the console to take you to the desired 
section.

Hint: Key Runstop brings up the command
line type: /functionname and hit F3 to 
find the function name in this document.

First section is the function list for
  quick syntax reference.

Second Section is the Function
  Description and Object file location.

Third section is the function soure
  files and disk title the files are
  located on.

Function List:
-----------------------------
Functions with a "$" in the name means
the function is for internal use by ML
functions you make.

void  c$finit( void ) /* NO HEADER, for ML routines only  */ 
char  getch  ( void ) /* CONIO.H */
char  inkey  ( void ) /* CONIO.H */
char  kbhit  ( void ) /* CONIO.H */
void* memmove( void* dest, void* src, unsigned len ) /* STRINGS.H */
void* memset ( void* dest, char c, unsigned size ) /* STRINGS.H */
char* strstr ( char* string, char* substr ) /* STRINGS.H */



Function Descriptions & Disk Locations:
-----------------------------
-------------------
C$FINIT() Loc: PCLIB01

void  c$finit( void )

Header: NO HEADER

Returns: None

Use this function internally in your ML
functions to copy c$parms ( Parameters )
to zero page starting at $4c. Maximum
parameters your function can have is
9 or zero page will be over written.
Call the function after c$funct_init
and it will also store the X reg at
address $4b for later retrieval in your
function so you can return a result from
your function in c$parms. Load the A reg
with the number of parameters your
function accepts.

Example:
; Copies X register and all parameters
; in that order to zero page starting at 
; $4b.

  jsr c$funct_init
  lda #5 ; Parameters your function takes
  jsr c$finit ; Copies X reg and all 
              ; parms to zero page.

-------------------
GETCH() Loc: PCLIB01

char getch   ( void )

Header: CONIO.H

Retruns: A key from the keyboard buffer.
  after waiting for a key to be pressed
  by the user.

Gets keyboard input like getc() but
does not echo the key to the screen.

Example:
/* Menu Choice */

#include<stdio.h>
#include<conio.h>

main()
{
  char key=0;

  puts("1) Add numbers");
  puts("2) Subtract numbers");
  puts("Q) Quit");

  while('q'!=(key=getch()))
  {
    switch(key)
      case '1':
        /* Do adding */
        break;
      case '2':
        /* Do subtracting */
        break;
      default:
        break;
  }
  puts("Boy, that was fun.");
}
-------------------
INKEY() Loc: PCLIB01

char  inkey  ( void )

Header: CONIO.H

Returns: A key from the keyboard buffer.

Gets keyboard input like getc() but
doesn't wait for keyboard input like
getc() does. Function is non standard
and can be replacd by using kbhit() and
getc() together. Function originates
from the BASIC statement inkey$ and has
similar behavoir.

Example:
/* Loop and check for key presses. */

#include<stdio.h>
#include<conio.h>

main()
{
  char key=0;

  /* Main loop */
  while('e' != key)
  {
    /* Check for key press but don't 
     * pause the loop.
     */
    key = inkey();

    /* Do other things */
  }

  /* 'e' key was pressed, loop exited 
   *  and program ended.
   */
}

-------------------
KBHIT() Loc: PCLIB01

char  kbhit  ( void )

Header: CONIO.H

Returns: Non zero if a key has been 
         pressed. The routine simply
         loads the value from memory 
         location $C6 and returns it.
         which means it can also be
         used to see how many characters 
         are currently in the keyboard
         buffer.

Example:
/* inkey() workaround. */

#include<stdio.h>
#include<conio.h>

main()
{
  char key=0;

  /* Main loop */
  while('e' != key)
  {
    /* Check for key press but don't 
     * pause the loop.
     */
    if(kbhit())
      key = getc(stdin);

    /* Do other things */
  }

  /* 'e' key was pressed, loop exited 
   *  and program ended.
   */
}

-------------------
MEMMOVE() Loc: PCLIB01

void* memmove( void* dest, 
               void* src, 
               unsigned len ) 

Header: STRINGS.H Loc: PCLIB01

Retruns: Pointer to dest.

void* dest:   Pointer to destination
              address in memory.
void* src:    Pointer to source address
              in memory.
unsigned len: Total bytes to copy.

Copies memory from a source location
to a destination location in RAM. The
location copied to may overlap with the
source memory location without conflict.

Example:
/* Copies a string over a string */

#include<strings.h>

main()
{
  char* str="ardvark ";

  puts( str );

  memmove( str+1, str, 8 );

  puts( str );
}

output: ardvark
        aardvark
-------------------
MEMSET() Loc: PCLIB01

void* memset( void* dest, 
              char c, 
              unsigned size )

Header: STRINGS.H Loc: PCHEAD01

Returns: Pointer to dest.
void* dest: Pointer to buffer.
char c: Byte to write
unsigned size: Total bytes to write
               0-65535.

Sets a memory range from 0 - 65535 to
a single byte.

Example:
/* Fills text screen with character 32 */
char* screen;

screen = (char*) memset(0x400, 32, 1000); 
-------------------
STRSTR() Loc: PCLIBS01 

char* strstr ( char* string, char* substr ) /* STRINGS.H */

Header: STRINGS.H Loc: PCLIBS01

Returns: Pointer to the first occurance
         of the substring found in 
         string or NULL if not found.

char* string: String to be searched.
char* substr: String to search for.

Searchs for a substring within a string
and if a match is found a pointer to
the index in string is returned. If not
found then NULL is returned. Both
strings may be any size.

Example:
/* Searchs for a substring in a string
and returns a pointer to it if found. */

#include<stdio.h>
#include<strings.h>

char* string = "Happy go lucky!";
char* substr = "lucky";

main()
{
  char* strptr, *subptr;

  strptr = string;
  subptr = substr;

  strptr = strstr( strptr, subptr );

  if( strptr )
  {
    printf("Substring found: %s\n", strptr);
  }
  else
  {
    printf("Substring not found.\n");
  }
}

Output:
Substring found: lucky!

